Deep reinforcement learning can be used to optimize personalized task recommendations by training an agent to interact with the user and learn from their behavior and feedback. The agent can be programmed with a reward function that encourages it to recommend tasks that are relevant and useful to the user.
To incorporate user feedback, the agent can be programmed to learn from both positive and negative feedback. For example, if the user completes a task that was recommended and rates it highly, the agent can learn to recommend similar tasks in the future. On the other hand, if the user ignores or dislikes a recommended task, the agent can learn to avoid similar recommendations.
To proactively anticipate and address user needs, the agent can be programmed with a predictive model that analyzes the user's behavior and makes recommendations based on their likely needs and preferences. For example, if the user frequently completes tasks related to a particular topic, the agent can proactively recommend related tasks in the future.
Here is an example Java code for a basic reinforcement learning agent that recommends tasks:
```
public class TaskAgent {
   private RewardFunction rewardFunction;
   private QTable qTable;

   public TaskAgent() {
      rewardFunction = new RewardFunction();
      qTable = new QTable();
   }

   public Task recommendTask(User user) {
      Task recommendedTask = null;
      double maxQValue = Double.NEGATIVE_INFINITY;

      for (Task task : TaskRepository.getAllTasks()) {
         double qValue = qTable.getQValue(user, task);
         if (qValue > maxQValue) {
            recommendedTask = task;
            maxQValue = qValue;
         }
      }

      if (recommendedTask != null) {
         rewardFunction.reward(user, recommendedTask);
         qTable.updateQValue(user, recommendedTask);
      }

      return recommendedTask;
   }
}
```
This agent uses a Q-table to store the expected reward for each possible action (in this case, recommending a task) given the current state (in this case, the user's preferences and needs). The agent updates the Q-table after each recommendation based on the user's feedback, and uses the Q-table to select the next recommendation.

